        "newspaperPageNumber":"45",
        "trailText":"<p>Nothing brings home the distance between pre- and post-baby existence like a holiday, says <strong>Liese Spencer</strong>. So this Suffolk hotel is a real eye-opener</p>",
        "headline":"Weekend travel special: Short break with kids in Suffolk",
        "body":"<p>Nothing brings home the cruel distance between your pre- and post-baby existence quite like holidays. Gone are those long, lazy lunches eating oysters with icy white wine at a table overlooking the sea; in their place, endless scavenging for high chairs, microwaves and baby-changing facilities.Which is why Luxury Family Holidays is such a genius idea. Scattered across the country, its grand country houses are properly swish, while at the same time offering cots, creches \u2013 even babysitters.</p><p>We visited Ickworth in Suffolk, National Trust pile and one-time seat of the late, impressively dissipated <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Hervey,_7th_Marquess_of_Bristol\" title=\"John Hervey\">John Hervey</a> (7th Marquess of Bristol, half-brother to It-Girl Victoria). Outside is a sprawl­ing estate to explore, with ancient church and vine­yard; inside the boutique decor allows strung-out parents to masquerade as world-weary jet-setters. Best of all, the prospect of a leisurely dinner free from wailing infants. I felt a guilty thrill at the child-unfriendly candle, white linen and goldfish bowl-sized glasses of red wine. Service was attentive and friendly, the locally sourced food well cooked and presented. And not a mashed banana in sight.</p><p>If the thronging numbers of ­children \u2013 in the pool, cycling in the driveway, enthroned in high chairs in the cafe \u2013 gave the smart surroundings a slightly surreal, Ballardian air, this was more than compensated for by just how easy the whole set-up made it to relax both with and without the kids. And, of course, ghettos can be supportive \u2013 no one here made you feel like a pariah for spoil­ing the sexy vibe with your sticky pots of puréed parsnip. Hervey, a devotee of cocaine, heroin and rent boys, is probably t­urning in his grave.</p><p><strong>Stay at</strong> <a href=\"http://www.ickworthhotel.co.uk/family_hotels_uk.asp\" title=\"Ickworth\">Ickworth</a>, from £170 per room per&nbsp;night&nbsp;(with breakfast and dinner).</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: travel/2010/jan/30/short-break-kids-suffolk-travel|2011-10-21T07:09:02+01:00|83beac0ea84956bccd26b085a7f279a096800522 -->",
