      "id":"travel/2010/jan/30/pasta-making-mantua-italy-winterson",
      "sectionId":"travel",
      "sectionName":"Travel",
      "webPublicationDate":"2010-01-30T00:10:52Z",
      "webTitle":"Weekend travel special: Jeanette Winterson in Italy",
      "webUrl":"http://www.guardian.co.uk/travel/2010/jan/30/pasta-making-mantua-italy-winterson",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/travel/2010/jan/30/pasta-making-mantua-italy-winterson",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"19",
        "trailText":"<p>The deli owner and novelist learns to make ravioli the traditional way</p>",
        "headline":"Weekend travel special: Jeanette Winterson in Italy",
        "body":"<p>Mantua is one of those Italian towns that lives in the past and the present with such style that history becomes a continuum \u2013 more like a series of connected rooms than a set of disappearances. Walking through its Renaissance squares, whether or not you choose to visit the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ducal_palace,_Mantua\" title=\"Ducal palace\">Ducal ­palace</a>, or the <a href=\"http://www.itis.mn.it/acqua/inglese/head/main2.htm\" title=\"Church of St Andrew\">Church of St Andrew</a>, or <a href=\"http://www.itis.mn.it/acqua/inglese/head/main.htm\" title=\"the Castle of St George\">the Castle of St George</a>, with its extraordinary ­<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrea_Mantegna\" title=\"Mantegnas\">Mantegnas</a>, the feeling is one of belonging to time as it ­really is; not vanished discontinuity, but ancestry. ­Perhaps only in Italy could past and present feel like one big ­family \u2013 noisy, eccentric, well ­preserved, respected.</p><p>No surprise, then, that everywhere I went ­during my food extravaganza in Mantua, I met generational families both proud of their cultural and ­gastronomic heritage, and keen to take it forward.</p><p>If you fly into <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/travel/2008/feb/03/verona.italy\" title=\"Verona\">Verona</a>, it would be worth taking a taxi straight to <a href=\"http://www.dalpescatore.com/main_en.asp\" title=\"dal Pescatore\">dal Pescatore</a>, an exquisite ­restaurant hidden in a park of birch trees outside Mantua. You will want to dress, because it is that kind of place, but although it is elegant and formal, it is not fussy, and the focus is on the food. One of&nbsp;the tasting menus gives tiny portions of catfish ravioli, hare with prunes, beef that breaks as it touches the fork, seafood in aspic as clear as glass&nbsp;that dissolves instantly on the tongue, ­releasing the delicate flavours inside; risotto of the season in a light broth, dainty, homemade breads with fresh butter churned by hand, and, of&nbsp;course, olive oil of such quality that, just on its&nbsp;own with a mop of bread and a draught of wine, it&nbsp;would be enough.</p><p>I was given a tour of the kitchens, where the grandmother was making salsa verde and the grandson was rapidly serrating the ravioli into ­expert triangles. The father took me round wine caves that became darker, colder, dustier and more expensive with every turn of the lock.</p><p>Yes, you could spend a great deal of money on your wine, but you could just as easily, as I&nbsp;did, enjoy half a bottle of Anselmi San Vincenzo Soave, followed by a 2004 Cardel Basio Pinot Noir. The man who made it came to shake hands. The daughter of the house sat down and talked with real passion about what was grown and made locally. They were all proud of what they were achieving, and their pleasure in the food and wine was serious but never pretentious. I ate and drank far too much, and ended the meal with a speciality Grappa di Barbaresco that I thought I&nbsp;didn't want, but that proved perfect against the scalding hot espresso and homemade chocolates.</p><p>It would be worth flying out even for one night to eat here.</p><p>The following morning I woke up feeling very well and walked straight out of my hotel into a small family bar for the inevitable good coffee and fresh orange juice. This Scotch-themed bar stocks every possible whisky and has photos of the Highlands. Nobody seems to mind, and drinks their Campari anyway. I love the cheerful bustle of those stand-up bars, where the coffee is never lukewarm and the shots of alcohol are little blasts to get you going.</p><p>Fortified, I set off round the Saturday morning Mantua market that sells everything from ­organic&nbsp;fruit to aged parmesan, fresh-hunted game, mountains of mushrooms and wonderful cheap wine, including the local lambrusco that is low in alcohol, but deliciously fruity and frizzante and, I&nbsp;discovered, ideal outdoors at 11am with a&nbsp;salami sandwich.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.agriturismomantova.it.\" title=\"Agriturismo In Mantova \">Agriturismo Mantua </a>organises farmers' ­markets and encourages tourists to visit farms, cheese- and winemakers. If you want to, you can&nbsp;stay with some of the families involved in keeping alive the gastronomy of Lombardy.</p><p>I really wanted to learn how to make pumpkin pasta. I have a deli, <a href=\"http://www.jeanettewinterson.com/verdes.asp\" title=\"Verde\">Verde</a>, in London, and Harvey Cabaniss, the chef who runs the operation, loves Italian food, but we both hate the prepacked ­commercial pastas ubiquitous in supermarkets. We&nbsp;wondered about making our own.</p><p>Pumpkins are to Mantua what potatoes are to&nbsp;Peru \u2013 varieties of every kind, shape, size and&nbsp;­colour, the incredible edibles, the ones for ­decoration and others that are strung into ­loofahs&nbsp;or grated into soap.</p><p>Agriturismo arranged for me to visit a three-­generational family who have a small restaurant, Merlin Cocai, where they grow a lot of their own food, and who offer cooking lessons. The grandmother was sitting by a wood-burning stove, watching bright-eyed as a squirrel as her daughter and grandson taught me how to make and roll the pasta dough, then spoon out the pumpkin filling, which has to be mixed with amaretti biscuits. The&nbsp;amaretti give it the distinctive sweetness that&nbsp;­either you love or you don't.</p><p>I was very bad at making same-size parcels, and I kept taking the little pillows over to la grandmamma, who in one twist and squeeze turned my lumpen, oozing misfire into elegant ravioli.</p><p>Then we all sat down at a long table and ate lunch, which was Everything You Can Do With A&nbsp;Pumpkin, including risotto, a chicken dish and a sweet torta for pudding. There was also pumpkin relish and pumpkin sauce.</p><p>I might have overdone it on the pumpkin class, but to be in that warm kitchen with plenty of ­lambrusco sloshing about and food being ­prepared with such skill and pleasure was in every sense, and for all the senses, a better world&nbsp;than the \"convenience\" food of the ­Anglo-American supermarket culture.</p><p>Food is our everyday experience, and to eat real food is essential to living a real life. The prepacked life is a swindle and a fake. This isn't about money or privilege; it's about what you value \u2013 the ­simple enjoyment of preparing and eating food, talking and drinking round the table.</p><p>There is no \"hidden\" Mantua, no secret ­special places to \"discover\", because Mantua itself is something of a secret special place. Verona or Venice are much more firmly on the map for the weekend visit, but Mantua is pretty marvellous, and nothing you do there will disappoint. Take a&nbsp;cool-bag to bring home lots from the market, and eat everything on the menus. Good food. Good life.</p><p><strong>Getting there </strong>BA flies from London Gatwick to V­erona, from £120 return; ba.com.</p><p><strong>Where to stay </strong><a href=\"http://www.anticadimoramantovana.it\" title=\"Hotel Antica Dimora Mantovana\">Hotel Antica Dimora Mantovana</a>; from \u20ac80 per room per night.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: travel/2010/jan/30/pasta-making-mantua-italy-winterson|2011-10-21T07:09:02+01:00|323544743a1037fc2e8be3683c7509c8ba472012 -->",
        "showInRelatedContent":"true",
        "lastModified":"2010-01-30T00:10:52Z",
        "hasStoryPackage":"true",
