      "id":"travel/2010/jan/30/travel-cycling-gastonomy-berry-france",
      "sectionId":"travel",
      "sectionName":"Travel",
      "webPublicationDate":"2010-01-30T00:10:02Z",
      "webTitle":"Weekend travel special: Cycling and eating in Berry, France | Matthew Fort",
      "webUrl":"http://www.guardian.co.uk/travel/2010/jan/30/travel-cycling-gastonomy-berry-france",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/travel/2010/jan/30/travel-cycling-gastonomy-berry-france",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"36",
        "trailText":"<p>Lance Armstrong he's not, but <strong>Matthew Fort </strong>wasn't about to let that stop him heading off on an eating tour along the Canal du Berry</p>",
        "headline":"Weekend travel special: Cycling and eating in Berry, France",
        "body":"<p>'This is La France profonde,\" said Madame Catherine ­Greninger, chateleine of ­<a href=\"http://www.manoirdumortier.com/\" title=\"Manoir du Mortier\">Manoir du Mortier</a>, deep in the Forêts de Tronçons in the heart of <a href=\"http://www.crwflags.com/fotw/flags/fr-berry.html\" title=\"Berry\">Berry</a>. And she was right. Oh, there's a good deal of industrial agriculture, vast prairie fields ­uncircumscribed by wall or fence. But these featureless plains are merely a disguise for an older, more rustic France, tucked away in coigns of the ­landscape. A France of country lanes, ­hamlets, fields of tussocky grass in which creamy <a href=\"http://www.cattle.com/BreedsofCattle/Images/charolais.jpg\" title=\"Charolais\">Charolais</a> and russet <a href=\"http://www.google.com/imgres?imgurl=http://www.limousin.co.uk/site/images/mainpage/Splashpage_r2_c2.jpg&amp;imgrefurl=http://www.limousin.co.uk/&amp;h=372&amp;w=563&amp;sz=32&amp;tbnid=E6Qw_1ircvUIBM:&amp;tbnh=88&amp;tbnw=133&amp;prev=/images%3Fq%3DLimousin%2Bcattle&amp;usg=__hIEqwNmsFd3TPzFJcGLuOS8h_4s=&amp;ei=HzhXS5acKYWD4QbZ8LClAw&amp;sa=X&amp;oi=image_result&amp;resnum=6&amp;ct=image&amp;ved=0CBYQ9QEwBQ\" title=\"Limousin\">Limousin</a> ­cattle munch meditatively. On the surface, it seems no different from familiar rural scenes at&nbsp;home, yet there is something ­unmistakably, ­irrepressibly French about it.</p><p>This is the countryside of grand châteaus, some serious and solid, others exuberant explosions of high Gothic architecture. These are&nbsp;the relics of France's long-departed grand families, who once exercised control throughout the country. But there are less showy establishments, too; ­unsung manor houses and fortified farms, ­testaments to Berry's agri­cultural wealth. This is the garden of France, watered by the Loire, the&nbsp;Cher, the ­Allier. It's always been a hugely ­productive area, with a distinctive gastronomic tradition. There's game from the forests of Sologne and Tronçons; walnuts and hazelnuts from the Auron valley; wild mushrooms, in their season; pike and zander from the rivers; pannequet berrichon, a crêpe made with mashed potato; le&nbsp;pâté berrichon, a pâté en crôute set with hard-boiled eggs, not ­unlike our ham pie; ­poulet en barbouille, chicken flambéed in brandy, cooked in cream blended with the bird's blood and liver, then thickened with egg yolk; truffat, a potato pie. It's the home of puff pastry, of tarte tatin; and famous for its goat's cheeses \u2013 crottin de Chavignol, Pouligny-Saint-Pierre, Selles-sur-Cher.</p><p>In short, it's solid, rustic, hearty food, long on taste and maybe a little short on subtlety. And it's just the kind of food I needed to sustain me as I&nbsp;cycled along the Ancien Canal du Berry. Built \u2013 or \"réalisé\", as the French so elegantly put it \u2013 ­between 1808 and 1840, 261km all told, with 97 locks to carry freight (coal, bricks, clay and iron) to and from <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Montlu%C3%A7on\" title=\"Montluon\">Montluçon</a> in the south, and to and from Fontblisse by way of V­allon-en-Sully and Saint-Amand-Montrond. And for my mode of transport, the vélo éléctrique, heir-apparent to the Vélo­Solex of beloved memory. It turned out to be an ingenious (and very French) contraption with a heavyweight battery, 10kg at a guess, that recharged nightly and sat below the saddle to provide a spirit-lifting nudge as ­energy sagged or legs began to shriek on steeper inclines. Not that it took the pedalling out of cycling, but it provided comfort to the ­unaccustomed cyclist. I'm no <a href=\"http://www.lancearmstrong.com/\" title=\"Lance Armstrong\">Lance ­Armstrong</a>. Easy does it, that's my motto.</p><p>And easy it was. Well, most of it. I had some trouble with the canal itself. When it was there, it&nbsp;was reassuringly broad and placid, its path marked by poplars, chestnuts and oaks. The ­trouble was, it had an awkward habit of ­disappearing completely from time to time. Still,&nbsp;the canal gave a general sense of direction and provided delightful diversions along the way,&nbsp;such as the <a href=\"http://www.auberge-magnette.com/fr.php?c_naam=8\" title=\"Auberge Magnette\">Auberge Magnette</a> at Reugny, walls cluttered with posters, bottles lining the glass shelves behind the bar, marble floor, spiky chandeliers, as if designed by <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernard_Buffet\" title=\"Bernard Buffet\">Bernard Buffet</a>. It&nbsp;was 3pm. \"Lunch?\" said Nelleke Hellemons, chef/barmaid/­proprietress. \"No problem.\" There&nbsp;was a&nbsp;petite friture of lentils with bacon, liver and ­onion, oily, warming, perfect to restore the spirit. And paupiettes de veau, light and ­perfumed with herbs. And exceptional cheeses. All for \u20ac19. Oh, and a ­pichet of ­unnamed red wine, a&nbsp;coffee and a&nbsp;calvados. And while I ate, a&nbsp;stream of pretty young girls passed by and ­disappeared through a&nbsp;door beyond, ­clutching ballgowns swathed in plastic, their mothers ­fussing ­behind, as surreal as the party in the lost château in Alain-Fournier's classic Le Grand Meaulnes, which is set hereabouts.</p><p>Then there was the dinner at the Manoir du Mortier. There was a fire at one end of the room, and a feeling that here was an ­immaculately ­civilised place. Dinner was communal. The food was impeccably French, haut bourgeois, country house, of a kind familiar to me from recipe books no longer read, grounded in the ingredients of the region, suave, generous in ­matters of butter and cream: soufflé de légumes; poulet l'Ardennais; cheeses with a Parma violet jelly; and \u2013 oh, the bliss of it \u2013 profiteroles bursting with coffee crème patissière and topped with coffee icing.</p><p>Then there was La Coralive at the tiny hamlet of St Just. It was an old-fashioned bistro of a kind I&nbsp;thought had vanished, complete with sexy ­barmaid cutting a swathe through the men who came and went for a drink, for lunch, for a chat. There were others, too, drifting in for a plate or two from the day's menu: terrine or salade de museau (pig's nose), followed by choucroute or duck. Having dispatched the salad, I dispatched the choucroute, and first-rate they were, too, while small dramas unfolded at tables around me. This&nbsp;was the daily routine, you felt:  normality. A mobile phone rang. \"Pas de ­commerce ici,\" snapped the barmaid. \"Dehors. Comme les cigarettes.\" The harassed mobile phone owner slunk obediently outside.</p><p>And there was the magical Huilerie Boussard in Dun-sur-Auron. It seemed typical of the region. There wasn't much to it: the beautifully set up if melancholy Musée du Canal du Berry, a fine gate tower and the remains of a medieval wall guarding the approaches from the river. Still, it had a sense of worth, of solidity, of civic pride, of a communal life long gone from English towns of similar size \u2013 butchers, bakers, grocers \u2013 and the huilerie sold ­walnut and ­hazelnut oil, specialities of the region. \"Where are they made?\" I asked the young man inside. \"Here,\" he said, gesturing to a room next door. And so it was, on machinery that must have been state of the art in about 1850 \u2013 a small granite stone revolving in a tray to crush the nuts; mats on which the crushed pulp is extruded; and a hydraulic press operated by pulleys and fly-wheels black with oil and age. The light was amber, the air rich in perfume of hazelnut and walnut. It&nbsp;was a vision of the working past. It seemed ­emblematic of the true pleasures of Berry.</p><p><strong>Getting there </strong><a href=\"http://www.eurostar.com\" title=\"Eurostar\">Eurostar</a> operates up to 20 daily services from ­London St Pancras International to Paris Gare de Nord, with return fares from £59.</p><p><strong>Stay at</strong> <a href=\"http://www.manoirdumortier.com/\" title=\"Manoir du Mortier\">Manoir du Mortier</a>, Le Mortier, Meaulne.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: travel/2010/jan/30/travel-cycling-gastonomy-berry-france|2011-10-21T07:09:02+01:00|e54a8fd1de01b4a843ff3512a7dcbe6bac6328e9 -->",
